*   Title: "Adjuvant docetaxel for node-positive breast cancer."
    *   Abstract details:
        *   Objective: Comparison of TAC vs. FAC as *adjuvant* chemotherapy.
        *   Participants: 1491 women with "operable node-positive breast cancer".
        *   Intervention: TAC or FAC "as adjuvant chemotherapy after surgery".
        *   Primary end point: Disease-free survival.
        *   Conclusion: TAC improves rates of disease-free and overall survival in women with "operable node-positive breast cancer".

    *   "Adjuvant chemotherapy": This usually implies treatment given after the primary treatment (surgery) to lower the risk of recurrence in patients with no clinical evidence of disease remaining.
    *   "Operable node-positive breast cancer": Operable means the primary tumor can be removed surgically, which is typical for localized or locally advanced disease. Node-positive means it has spread to regional lymph nodes, but not necessarily distant sites.
    *   "Disease-free survival": This endpoint is used when patients are expected to be free of disease after initial treatment.

    *   LOCALIZED: Patients with localized/locally advanced disease (e.g., operable, node-positive) that has not formed distant metastases.
    *   METASTATIC: Distant metastatic disease.
    *   BOTH: Both localized and metastatic.
    *   NEITHER: Neither localized nor metastatic (e.g., prevention trial).
    *   UNCLEAR: Not enough info.

    The trial focuses on "operable node-positive breast cancer" and "adjuvant chemotherapy after surgery". In oncology, "adjuvant" and "operable" specifically point towards localized or locally advanced disease (Stages I-III) rather than metastatic disease (Stage IV).

    "We randomly assigned 1491 women with axillary node-positive breast cancer to six cycles of treatment with either TAC or FAC as adjuvant chemotherapy after surgery." OR "Adjuvant chemotherapy with TAC, as compared with FAC, significantly improves the rates of disease-free and overall survival among women with operable node-positive breast cancer."

    "Adjuvant chemotherapy" and "operable node-positive breast cancer" together confirm this is for patients without distant metastases.
